132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 645
H.P. 413 House of Representatives, February 25, 2025
An Act to Change the Size and Composition of the Board of
Directors of the Maine Health Data Organization
Submitted by the Maine Health Data Organization pursuant to Joint Rule 204.
Received by the Clerk of the House on February 20, 2025. Referred to the Committee on
Health Coverage, Insurance and Financial Services pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered
printed pursuant to Joint Rule 401.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative MATHIESON of Kittery.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 22 MRSA §8703, sub-§2, as amended by PL 2009, c. 71, §6, is further
3 amended to read:
4 2. Board of directors. The organization operates under the supervision of a board of
5 directors, which consists of 20 12 voting members and one nonvoting member.
6 A. The Governor shall appoint 18 11 board members in accordance with the following
7 requirements. Appointments by the Governor are not subject to review or
8 confirmation.
9 (1) Four Two members must represent consumers chosen from a list provided by
10 a statewide organization representing consumers. For the purposes of this section,
11 "consumer" means a person who is not affiliated with or employed by a 3rd-party
12 payor, a provider or an association representing those providers or those 3rd-party
13 payors.
14 (2) Three Two members must represent employers. One member must be chosen
15 from a list provided by a health management statewide purchasing coalition in this
16 State. One member must be chosen from a list provided by a statewide chamber
17 of commerce.
18 (3) Two members must represent 3rd-party payors chosen from a list provided by
19 a statewide organization representing 3rd-party payors.
20 (4) Nine Four members must represent health care providers. Two One health
21 care provider members member must represent hospitals and health systems that
22 include hospitals chosen from a list provided by the Maine Hospital Association a
23 statewide association representing hospitals and health systems that include
24 hospitals. Two health care provider members must be physicians or
25 representatives of physicians, one may not be affiliated with a hospital or a health
26 system that includes a hospital and must be chosen from a list provided by the
27 Maine Medical Association and one chosen from a list provided by the Maine
28 Osteopathic Association a statewide association that represents health care
29 providers. One health care provider member must be a pharmacist chosen from a
30 list provided by a statewide association of pharmacists. One provider member
31 must be a doctor of chiropractic chosen from a list provided by a statewide
32 chiropractic association. One provider member must be a representative, chosen
33 from a list provided by the Maine Primary Care Association, of a federally
34 qualified health center. One provider member must be a pharmacist chosen from
35 a list provided by the Maine Pharmacy Association. One provider member must
36 be a mental health provider chosen from a list provided by the Maine Association
37 of Mental Health Services. One provider member must represent a home health
38 care company.
39 (5) One member must represent the pharmaceutical industry, including
40 pharmaceutical manufacturers, wholesale distributors and pharmacy benefits
41 managers, chosen from a list provided by a statewide association representing life
42 sciences companies.
43 B. The commissioner shall appoint one member who is an employee of the department
44 to represent the State's interest in maintaining health data and to ensure that information
Page 1 - 132LR0530(01)

415 collected is available for determining public health policy Director of the Office of
426 MaineCare Services or the director’s designee shall serve as a member of the board.
3 D. The Executive Director of Dirigo Health, or a designee of the executive director
4 who is an employee of Dirigo Health, shall serve as a voting member.
5 E. The Commissioner of Professional and Financial Regulation, or the commissioner's
6 designee who is an employee of the Department of Professional and Financial
7 Regulation, shall serve in a nonvoting, consultative capacity.
8 F. The executive director of the organization shall serve as a nonvoting member of the
9 board.
10 Sec. 2. 22 MRSA §8703, sub-§3, ¶A, as amended by PL 2005, c. 253, §4, is further
11 amended to read:
12 A. The terms of board members appointed by the Governor are determined as follows.
13 (1) Initial terms are staggered. One consumer, one employer, one 3rd-party payor
14 and 3 providers shall serve one-year terms. Two consumers, one employer, one
15 3rd-party payor and 3 providers shall serve 2-year terms.
16 (2) After the initial terms, members Members appointed by the Governor shall
17 serve full 3-year terms and shall continue to serve until their successors have been
18 appointed.
19 (3) Board members may serve 3 full terms consecutively.
20 SUMMARY
2211 This bill changes the size of the Maine Health Data Organization board of directors
2222 from a board with 20 voting members and one nonvoting member to a board with 12 voting
2233 members and one nonvoting member. It changes the composition of the board by adding
2244 as a voting member a representative from the pharmaceutical industry and adding as the
2255 nonvoting member the executive director of the Maine Health Data Organization. It
2266 removes the provision regarding staggering of initial terms.
